I liked the whole setup with judge_entry, as it felt like it had some really nice properties:
1) It is easy for everyone to verify.
2) Unlike RSA, it is not just "solve this one example at this bit size", yet it doesn't let people freely construct problems.  It feels like a really nice compromise to encourage creativity -- if someone finds a property that is "dense" enough that you can search through some seeds with a good chance of finding it, it is still possible. (for example, look at what akashnil did, to boost things a bit -- that was neat)
3) It asks a slightly weaker question: find the order of any non-identity element. This is easy to directly verify (#1), and also encourages creativity as this may allow different approaches.

@pulledpork The plan in the future is to use the format of RSA breakage challenges where there are bounties posted indefinitely which can be claimed by anyone at any time for breaks of specific challenges at different sizes

Or instead of a contest with a fixed time limit, maybe bounties for different bit limits sort of like RSA did so people could see what crazy effort was required to break even the mid sized numbers. (You could even keep the format the same with judge_entry.py -- I'm particularly interested in testing the hypothesis that finding small factors is hard, or at least that is what I'm looking into now, as it feels like a more manageable way to chip at the problem (although admittedly, I've not made much progress so far)).

Now that we see 240bits took 12 days to calculate, just set a lower bound of 300bits or something, so that someone needs to come up with something new, or put in heroic effort with old techniques (parrallelize the known sub-exponential algorithm?).
I do wish they would do another track2 competition.  I didn't have time to read up on all the math for it last time, and now I've been kind of bit by this problem and am still looking into it.

Damn, implementation was already available before the competition started. All that was needed was to find and run it! I don't think anybody knew about it, including the organizers, when the competition started.

edit.body:
@pulledpork I can confirm that the claassgroup isn't cyclic for discriminant =-106663. It is isomorphic to the direct sum of Z_33 and Z_3. Is the cyclic nature claimed anywhere, I don't think it's a contradiction. For the security of VDF, all that is needed is the base element (2, 1, X) has very large order which is hard to find. It may not always be a generator of the group.

Yes the order is always odd if discriminant is negative prime. Notice that order = number of reduced forms. Every reduced form is (a,b,c) where c >= a >= b > -a (Definition 5.1 and 5.3 in classgroup doc). If a = c, then -d = b^2 - 4a^2 factorizes into two nontrivial factors, contradiction. If a = b, -d = a^2 - 4ac. a must be 1 because d is prime. This is the unique identity element (1, 1, X). For all other reduced form (a,b,c): (a,-b,c) is also a distinct reduced form. Hence the order is odd.
